Thus the lex Licinia, one of the earliest agrarian laws, proposed that no one should occupy as tenant os the state (possideret) more than 500 jugera os the public land, and that the remainder should be allotted as property to the poorer classes. These agrarian laws related only to the public land, occupied and rented by the patriciam, as possessores, and had nothing to do with private property.
